          <h1>Common Blog</h1>

          <div class="blog" id="outer_block_57">
            <h2>Back to the airwaves</h2>
            <a href="http://theciviccommons.com/user/9">
              <img src="http://s3.amazonaws.com/com.theciviccommons.production/avatars/9/large/Moulthrop1.jpg" class="blog-pic" alt="Dan Moulthrop" />
            </a>
            <div class='blog_inner'>
              <p>
              I love radio. There's nothing quite like the intimacy it allows. When it's done well, it feels like a conversation
              you're already a part of. Those of us who have steady radio habits know exactly what I'm referring to. That's part
              of why it was so difficult for me to leave my last job at WCPN, and also why I was so excited when Mark Krieger
              of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WJCU">WJCU</a> (88.7 FM) invited the Civic Commons to take advantage of an
              8:30 a.m. slot that is opening Saturday mornings.
              </p>
              <p>
              So this Saturday morning (1/22) the Civic Commons is taking to the airwaves. Our goal with the radio show is to take
              a different sort of approach to the issues we're dealing with every day across Northeast Ohio. Our main goal is to
              bring your voice to the airwaves as much as possible. We'll be starting off by using the
              <a href="http://www.theciviccommons.com/principles">CC principles</a> as a way to examine what's happening in the
              region. For a variety of reasons, we thought we'd start with transparency. That gives us a chance to examine the
              recent transition to a new form government in Cuyahoga County and some of the stumbles along the way. (If you want
              a preview, you can hear the
              <a href="http://s3.amazonaws.com/com.theciviccommons.production/attachments/3389/original/rogers-greenspan%20intv.mp3?1295262987">entire, unedited interview</a>
              I did with newly installed council members Julian Rogers and Dave Greenspan.)
              </p>
              <p>
              We hope you'll tune in! And if you can't, check back here for the podcast.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="post_info">
              posted by <a href="http://social.theciviccommons.com/user/9">Dan Moulthrop</a> on January 08, 2011
            </div>

         </div>

         <div class="blog" id="outer_block_57">
            <h2>Lessons from the Mobile Town Hall</h2>
            <a href="http://theciviccommons.com/user/9">
              <img src="http://s3.amazonaws.com/com.theciviccommons.production/avatars/9/large/Moulthrop1.jpg" class="blog-pic" alt="Dan Moulthrop" />
            </a>
            <div class='blog_inner'>
              <p>
              Last Wednesday, we spent the lunch hour with about 20 or 30 citizens and Akron Deputy Mayor Dave Lieberth at the
              public library and the municipal building. <%= link_to "The conversation", conversation_path(82) %> was fantastic,
              and people weren't even in the same room. What we're finding is that technology can actually bring people closer
              to the officials who work for them. We connected the dep mayor to his constituents via Skype, and that prompted a
              really interesting question. The mayor's office is only a few blocks away, so why bother with the technology? My
              colleague Noelle Celeste supplied the perfect response: Would you walk those few blocks to ask that question? The
              answer to that is usually 'No.'
              </p> 
              <p>
              So, we see this as a success for a few reasons
              </p> 
              <p>
              --we were able to bring government right to where people live their lives
              </p>
              <p>
              --the technology created a different kind of conversation, one that doesn't feel like an ordinary town hall performance
              </p>
              <p>
              --we heard from a lot of people who don't typically get heard from
              </p>
              <p>
              We learned a few lessons, too, some about logistics (we could use twitter to preview who's coming next for both the dep.
              mayor and the public to see, for instance), some about other ways to extend the conversation (stream it live), some about
              how the location may dictate the kind of participants you get (who would you see at Lock 3 in the summer, or the Mustard
              Seed Market, for instance). The most important lesson, though, would be to make sure we have a community advocate of some
              sort on hand to help connect people to the resources they need, particularly when they bring up issues such as prisoner
              re-entry or child protective services.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="post_info">
              posted by <a href="http://social.theciviccommons.com/user/9">Dan Moulthrop</a> on January 08, 2011
            </div>

          </div>

          <div class="blog" id="outer_block_55">
            <h2>Mobile Town Hall</h2>
            <a href="http://social.theciviccommons.com/user/9">
              <img src="http://s3.amazonaws.com/com.theciviccommons.production/avatars/9/large/Moulthrop1.jpg" class="blog-pic" alt="Dan Moulthrop"/>
            </a>
            <div class='blog_inner'>
              <p>
              To kick off the New Year, we’re hosting a special Town Hall meeting in Akron next Wednesday, January 5th. This isn’t
              your usual Town Hall, though. It’s more like an opportunity for citizens to get some real one-on-one time with one of
              the most important (and most accessible) elected officials in Akron--Deputy Mayor Dave Lieberth.
              </p>
              <p>
              The dep. mayor wants to hear from Akronites on all sorts of stuff: what you'd  like to see improved in Akron, a
              New Year’s resolution the city should take on, a big idea for improving the city, a pet pothole that’s been bugging
              you. What makes this a little different is that we're doing this with a technological twist--Lieberth will be connecting
              with citizens via Skype and we'll be recording the whole thing and then posting it online for others to interact with.
              </p>
              <p>
              (Sure, the dep mayor could walk down the library, but this is just a proof of concept--imagine how this could be used to
              connect city hall to all the branch libraries at once, or all the community centers in town.) 
              </p>
              <p>
              Here are the details:
              <br />
              WHEN: January 5th, noon
              <br />
              WHERE: Akron Public Library, Garden
              Corridor, near the High Street entrance
              <br />
              SIGN UP: <a href="mailto:jasonrussell@theciviccommons.com">jasonrussell@theciviccommons.com</a>
              <br />
              Feel free to come join us to watch as well, the conversation will be broadcast for everyone to see.
              <br />
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="post_info">
              posted by <a href="http://social.theciviccommons.com/user/9">Dan Moulthrop</a> on December 30, 2010
            </div>

          </div>

