          <div class="blog" id="outer_block_36">
            <h2>What exactly are we doing here?</h2>
            <a href="http://social.theciviccommons.com/user/9">
              <img src="http://s3.amazonaws.com/com.theciviccommons.production/avatars/9/large/Moulthrop1.jpg" class="blog-pic" alt="Dan Moulthrop"/>
            </a>
            <div class='blog_inner'>
              <p>
              The Civic Commons is a grand experiment. We opened the doors last week to a group of you—close to 200 so far—to
              help us test this web environment. And we realize it’s maybe not entirely clear what you can do here and why you
              would want to do it. One of the most common bits of feedback we received last week goes something like this:
              “It feels like the conversation has already happened,” or “I feel like I’d be interrupting if I jump in.” or
              “This system is baffling. I keep getting entirely different windows to respond and they're all quirky.”
              <b>This kind of feedback is great. It tells us that what we think we've created isn't working right yet</b>.
              </p>
              <p>So, I'm going to try to explain exactly what we’re doing and you can tell me how we might do it better. Conversation
              is basically the engine of civic engagement. It’s how we exchange ideas, how we organize, how we share information with
              one another. Important civic conversations are happening all over the place, all the time, and <strong>what we’re trying
                to create is a place and practice for those conversations to continue, to be ongoing, and to involve more people.</strong>
              </p>
              <p>
              So, take <a href="http://theciviccommons.com/conversations/27">the conversation about urban farming</a>—we transcribed a
              City Club event from last Spring and created an opportunity for anyone to join the conversation anywhere in the conversation.
              Where you see &quot;No responses&quot; or &quot;3 responses&quot;--those are all places where you can jump in and add your
              thoughts, ask a question, suggest an action, or post some piece of information you think is relevant.  We’re used to just
              seeing things presented and then commenting on them at the end. This is different. We’re trying to make it possible to allow
              real, authentic, valuable participation by everyone, even people who weren’t there.
              </p>
              <p>
              Clearly, we haven’t figured this out yet, so help us. What would make this work better?
              </p>
              <p>
              A couple things we’re contemplating are notifications (if someone comments on something you said or in a conversation you’re
              following, you get a heads up), and also the ability to ask a question of a particular conversation participant (or even
              someone who’s not there, who could be invited to join the Commons). But those could wind up baffling people, too. So your
              suggestions here are welcome. We’re listening.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="post_info">
              posted by <a href="http://social.theciviccommons.com/user/9">Dan Moulthrop</a> on November 22, 2010
            </div>

          </div>

