          <div class="blog" id="outer_block_2">
            <h2>Can you volunteer at the Civic Commons?</h2>
            <a href="http://social.theciviccommons.com/user/9">
              <img src="http://s3.amazonaws.com/com.theciviccommons.production/avatars/9/large/Moulthrop1.jpg" class="blog-pic" alt="Dan Moulthrop"/>
            </a>
            <div class='blog_inner'>
              <p>
              We get this question a fair bit, and the answer, of course, is <strong>yes</strong>. There’s lots of ways you can volunteer at
              the Commons. Volunteering is one of those things that simply makes life better. We help someone else or some organization, and
              in return, we get a warm fuzzy feeling and the sense that we’re more of the person we want to be and less of the person who
              guiltily eats chocolate chips out of the peanut butter jar with a spoon while watching “Glee.” And what’s great about volunteering
              at the Commons is that it’s not quite like a lot of other volunteer gigs.
              </p>
              <p>
              A few months back I heard was listening to <a href="http://www.wcpn.org/soi">the radio program I used to host</a>. They were
              talking about how to make local governments more efficient, a topic in which I have a keen interest. This guy called in,
              identifying himself as a listener from Lakewood and a former economic development professional. He said he didn’t think he
              ever created any jobs, and he didn’t think economic development professionals ever create any jobs, except for more economic
              development professionals.
              </p>
              <p>
              Well, I got to wondering, what if we had fifty or a hundred volunteers across this corner of the state, and we could ask them
              to go their city’s economic development department or community liaison, and ask them three questions:
              </p> 
              <p>
              What was your economic development budget for each of the last three years?
              </p>
              <p>
              What economic development strategies did you employ in each of the last three years?
              </p>
              <p>
              How many jobs did those strategies create?
              </p>
              <p>
              Then, we could get the answers back and create something that looks like <a href="http://www.informationisbeautiful.net/visualizations/snake-oil-supplements/">this</a>
              -- except it would be about economic development and not whether nutritional supplements are snake oil.
              </p>
              <p>
              So, to pull that off, we can use volunteer reporters, data crunchers, designers, organizers. And elsewhere in the commons, we’ve
              got room for volunteer writers, editors, conversation moderators (or as one of our volunteers put it, “conversation shepherds”),
              researchers, photographers, transcribers, coders, and social media mavens. I suspect there are a few volunteer categories I’ve
              forgotten about. Which is to say if you’ve got an idea about how you’d like to lend your talents to the project, you can send an
              email to us (<a href="mailto:volunteer@theciviccommons.com">volunteer@theciviccommons.com</a>), and we can certainly find a place
              for you.
              </p>
              <p>
              The other part of this is that volunteering for the Commons shouldn’t necessarily take a ton of your time (unless you want it to).
              If you’ve got ten minutes a week, we can use it. And it's worth pointing out at the risk of undermining this call for volunteers,
              that just participating in a conversation here or suggesting one that you think ought to be launched is a way to make your
              community stronger.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="post_info">
              posted by <a href="http://social.theciviccommons.com/user/9">Dan Moulthrop</a> on November 03, 2010
            </div>

          </div>

          <div class="blog" id="outer_block_1">
            <h2>A Great Experiment</h2>
            <a href="http://social.theciviccommons.com/user/9">
              <img src="http://s3.amazonaws.com/com.theciviccommons.production/avatars/9/large/Moulthrop1.jpg" class="blog-pic" alt="Dan Moulthrop" />
            </a>
            <div class='blog_inner'>
              <p>
              The CC team spent a beautiful Saturday afternoon recently at Cleveland State’s student center, participating in Spotlight
              Cleveland, an event organized by Senator Sherrod Brown’s office to bring together local organizations who have volunteer
              and networking opportunities for young professionals. We participated for all the reasons you’d expect us to participate—to
              connect with other organizations and interested citizens. But what really piqued our interest was the chance to see if we
              could use an unconventional setting—the ballroom expo—for unconventional civic engagement.
              </p>
              <p>
              Here’s what we did (and big ups to project directors Lia Lockert and Jason Russell for masterminding this effort):
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                We commandeered a corner of the ballroom with two couches a couple of small tables, and, crucially, a small table lamp
                (for ambience).
                </li>
                <li>
                We invited people to sit down with complete strangers, pick a question out of a hat and talk about it.
                </li>
                <li>
                We recorded it.
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
              Here are a few things I noticed:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                People like to be asked their thoughts on issues that matter (in this case, questions were about what drives people to
                choose one community over another, and about the regional identity of this corner of the state)
                </li>
                <li>
                Conversations don’t really require a whole lot of active moderation
                </li>
                <li>
                Unconventional settings can be turned into surprising places for engagement.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
              I’ve spent a lot of the last five years actively managing and moderating formal and informal conversations, and I was
              happily surprised to find that role was rendered almost irrelevant. In conversations, people naturally rise into roles,
              asking questions of one another and following up on one another’s comments. The conversations were civil and compelling;
              there was a diversity of perspectives, everyone participated. In some ways, this exemplified a lot of the principles we
              put at the center of our work here, the desire to strive to be diverse, participatory, civil, credible, transparent,
              entrepreneurial and optimistic.
              </p>
              <p>
              So, if part of the secret it seems is to set up opportunities and then get out of the way so people can just engage with
              one another, here’s the challenge: how do you do this online? How do you take one of our online conversations—whether they
              begin with a live event or not—and foster the same kind of self-directed energy we found with the participants at Spotlight
              Cleveland?
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="post_info">
              posted by <a href="http://social.theciviccommons.com/user/9">Dan Moulthrop</a> on November 03, 2010
            </div>

